Converts a `steno::editor::Event` keystroke stream into a Plover-compatible value string — the textual format Plover dictionary entries use to represent typed output plus special keys.

The core subtlety is in `escape_space_run`: a single interior space is emitted literally only when both neighboring characters exist and neither is `\n`; otherwise every space in the run is escaped individually as `{^ ^}` (not batched), because a lone space touching a boundary or newline is one Plover would silently eat. `push_escaped_char` escapes `{`, `}`, `\n`, and `\t` for Plover's syntax — any new Plover-significant character must be added here too, and this escaping logic has no other copy in the crate to stay in sync with.

`Serializer` batches consecutive `Event::Text` and `Event::Key { key: Enter, .. }` events into one pending text span (`text`), and consecutive other `Event::Key` events into one pending `{#...}` group; `Event::Mark` is dropped entirely (invisible in output). Switching between text and key events flushes the other accumulator first, so text and key groups never interleave within a flush — `flush_text` escapes the whole pending span at once via `escape_text`, meaning escaping decisions (like the space-run logic) see full context across multiple original `Text` events if they weren't interrupted by a key group. `Enter` is special-cased to append literal `\n` characters into the text span (repeated `n` times) rather than becoming a `{#...}` key, so it participates in text escaping instead of key grouping.

Public API: `escape_text(s: &str) -> String` (standalone escaper, reusable outside full serialization) and `serialize(events: &[Event]) -> String` (drives the whole pipeline, no surrounding `{^}` affixes added — caller must add those if needed). Both are `#[must_use]`. Depends on `super::{Event, KeyName}` from the parent `editor` module — `KeyName::name()` supplies the literal key names written into `{#...}` groups, so key display names live there, not in this file.